li.p:
AP = \begin{bmatrix}
A\vvec_1 \amp A\vvec_2
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
3\vvec_1 \amp -6\vvec_2
\end{bmatrix}.

PD = \begin{bmatrix}
\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \amp 0 \\
0 \amp -6\\
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
3\vvec_1 \amp -6\vvec_2
\end{bmatrix}
.  Comparing the result of this part of the activity
to the previous, we see that AP = PD.

 We have

	    D^2=\mattwo4001, D^3=\mattwo800{-1}, \ldots,
	    D^k=\mattwo{2^k}00{(-1)^k}\text{.}

 We can also see this by noting that

	    \begin{aligned}
	    A^2 \amp = (PDP^{-1})(PDP^{-1})
	    = PD(P^{-1}P)DP^{-1} \\
	    \amp = PDIDP^{-1}
	    = PD^2P^{-1}\text{.}\\
	    \end{aligned}

example.p:
Notice that D^k = \begin{bmatrix}
1^k \amp 0 \\
0 \amp 0.2^k \\
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp 0 \\
0 \amp 0.2^k
\end{bmatrix}
.  As k increases, 0.2^k becomes
closer and closer to zero.  This means that for very large
powers k, we have

  D^k \approx \begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp 0 \\
  0 \amp 0 \\
  \end{bmatrix}

and therefore

  A^k = PD^kP^{-1} \approx P\begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp 0 \\
  0 \amp 0 \\
  \end{bmatrix}P^{-1} =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  \frac 34 \amp \frac 34 \\
  \frac 14 \amp \frac 14
  \end{bmatrix}.

sidebyside.p:
The next activity shows that C has a simple geometric effect on \real^2. First, however, we will use polar coordinates to rewrite C. As shown in the figure, the point (a,b) defines r, the distance from the origin, and \theta, the angle formed with the positive horizontal axis. We then have
\begin{aligned} a \amp {}={} r\cos\theta \\ b \amp {}={} r\sin\theta\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
Notice that the Pythagorean theorem says that r=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}.
